# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Units
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:unit-3236
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Searching and sorting algorithms"@en ;
  curric:slug "searching-and-sorting-algorithms" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will have opportunities to analyse, interpret, modify, and
  implement a range of searching and sorting algorithms. They will have the opportunity to
  compare the features and efficiency of these algorithms and make suggestions about the
  most suitable algorithm for a given task."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As pupils’ understanding of algorithms develops, they are ready to explore
  how computers organise and process data efficiently. This unit introduces common searching
  and sorting algorithms, helping pupils see how these processes mirror everyday
  problem-solving. By analysing how algorithms differ in efficiency and suitability, pupils
  learn to think critically about the design and performance of computational solutions.
  Understanding these techniques at this stage strengthens logical reasoning and prepares
  pupils to make informed decisions when creating and optimising their own programs.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3236-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3236-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3236-3 ;
  curric:id "3236"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.213191Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-programming ,
    oakcurric:thread-algorithms-and-data-structures .

oakcurric:unit-3244
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Network fundamentals"@en ;
  curric:slug "network-fundamentals" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will be develop their understanding of computer networks by
  looking at network models and the tasks performed by network hardware. They will discover
  the differences between wired and wireless transmission media and the factors that can
  affect the performance of a network."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Having already explored the basics of networks, pupils are now ready to
  examine how they function in greater depth. Understanding network models, hardware and data
  transmission is essential for appreciating how modern communication systems operate. By
  analysing how networks are built and managed, pupils develop a deeper awareness of the
  systems that underpin digital communication and the importance of reliability, speed and
  security in an interconnected world.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3244-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3244-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3244-3 ;
  curric:id "3244"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.377102Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-networks ,
    oakcurric:thread-impact-of-technology .

oakcurric:unit-3238
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Data science: AI and machine learning"@en ;
  curric:slug "data-science-ai-and-machine-learning" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces pupils to the emerging field of data science. They will
  explore what AI systems are and the different categories of AI. The concept of machine
  learning and how models are driven by data will be explored. They will also consider the
  ethical and wider implications of AI systems."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Having previously explored the basics of artificial intelligence and
  machine learning, pupils now deepen their understanding of how these systems work and
  influence society. They examine predictive and generative AI, considering how such tools are
  trained and used. Reflecting on the social and ethical implications encourages pupils to
  think deeply about the role of AI in their lives and the responsibilities of those who design
  and use it.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3238-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3238-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3238-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3238-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3238-5 ;
  curric:id "3238"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.488927Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-impact-of-technology ,
    oakcurric:thread-artificial-intelligence .

oakcurric:unit-3235
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Representation of text, images and sound"@en ;
  curric:slug "representation-of-text-images-and-sound" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils will discover how letters, images and sounds are represented
  with binary digits. They will also explore the factors that impact the quality of those
  representations and investigate the effects these quality choices have on file size."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As pupils’ understanding of how digital data is represented develops, they
  are ready to explore how computers store and manage different types of information. This unit
  helps pupils understand how text, images and sound are encoded, revealing how binary
  underpins digital media. By examining character sets and file compression, pupils begin to
  recognise the trade-offs between quality, file size and efficiency. Learning this now helps
  them appreciate the design choices that allow technology to balance performance,
  accessibility and user experience in the digital world.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3235-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3235-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3235-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3235-4 ;
  curric:id "3235"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:23.491373Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-data-and-information .

oakcurric:unit-3248
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Cyber threats and security"@en ;
  curric:slug "cyber-threats-and-security" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit enables pupils to develop awareness of a range of cybersecurity threats
  that impact the world and us as individuals. They will explore different forms of attack,
  both non-automated and automated and how encryption tools can be used to protect
  communication."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As pupils begin to rely more heavily on digital systems, it is vital that
  they understand the threats these systems face and how to defend against them. This unit
  builds awareness of cybersecurity, exploring both the human and technical factors behind
  attacks. By understanding the possible dangers and how organisations reduce vulnerabilities,
  pupils learn how to protect themselves and appreciate the importance of secure, resilient
  systems in today’s interconnected world.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3248-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3248-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3248-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3248-4 ;
  curric:id "3248"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.023147Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-impact-of-technology ,
    oakcurric:thread-safety-and-security .

oakcurric:unit-3237
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Data compression"@en ;
  curric:slug "data-compression" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will be introduced to the concept of data compression and why
  it is needed. The will compare lossy and lossless compression methods and their typical
  uses. They will have the opportunity to compression methods such as run length encoding
  (RLE) and Huffman coding."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """At this stage, pupils are ready to think more critically about how digital
  information is managed in a world that depends on efficiency and communication. Understanding
  data compression helps them grasp the balance between quality, speed, and storage. Learning
  about how data is reduced and transmitted develops analytical thinking and decision-making,
  encouraging pupils to weigh trade-offs and justify choices. These skills extend beyond
  Computer Science, supporting logical reasoning and informed judgement across all areas of
  learning.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3237-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3237-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3237-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3237-4 ;
  curric:id "3237"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.086284Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-data-and-information .

oakcurric:unit-3246
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "The internet and web technologies"@en ;
  curric:slug "the-internet-and-web-technologies" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will explore how data travels across the internet. They will
  explore how protocols define communication between devices and the purpose of common
  network protocols. They will investigate the risks to networks and the methods that can be
  used to protect a network."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit further develops pupils' understanding of network communication
  by exploring how the internet is network of connected networks. They learn about the
  protocols that enable devices connected to the internet to communicate with one another and
  how these protocols are arranged in protocol stacks such as TCP/IP. Pupils will learn how a
  web browser works and the role of DNS and IP addressing in the WWW. The unit concludes by
  pupils exploring common threats to networks and the methods that can be used to protect
  networks.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3246-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3246-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3246-3 ;
  curric:id "3246"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.233143Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-networks ,
    oakcurric:thread-computing-systems ,
    oakcurric:thread-safety-and-security .

oakcurric:unit-3252
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Using physical computing to create a robot buggy"@en ;
  curric:slug "using-physical-computing-to-create-a-robot-buggy" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces pupils to physical computing by building a robotic buggy.
  They will use a Raspberry Pi Pico microcontroller to explore inputs and outputs, and
  utilise a range of hardware components, including motors, reflective optical sensors,
  LEDs, and an ultrasonic sensor."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit progresses pupils' knowledge and understanding of physical
  computing. It starts with the creation of basic circuits and builds up their usage and
  confidence each lesson, as it incorporates programming a new piece of hardware with different
  inputs and outputs. By the end of the unit, pupils should have a good understanding of
  microcontrollers and embedded systems in general, as well as conceptual and practical
  experience of physically connecting input/output devices to GPIO pins, obtaining data from
  sensors, and using this data to make decisions.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3252-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3252-2 ;
  curric:id "3252"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.344262Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-programming ,
    oakcurric:thread-computing-systems ,
    oakcurric:thread-design-and-development .

oakcurric:unit-3233
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Representation of numbers"@en ;
  curric:slug "representation-of-numbers" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will be reminded of how the base-10 number system works before
  being introduced to the base-2 number system. They will perform conversions between binary
  and decimal and recognise the rules of binary addition and subtraction. They will be
  introduced to hexadecimal and its uses."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Understanding how data is represented and compressed helps pupils
  appreciate the invisible processes that make digital communication and storage possible. This
  unit strengthens logical thinking and numeracy while revealing how efficiency, accuracy and
  structure are central to all digital systems. Learning this now deepens pupils’ awareness of
  the design decisions that shape the technology they use every day.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3233-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3233-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3233-3 ;
  curric:id "3233"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.683338Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-data-and-information .

oakcurric:unit-3241
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Using data science and AI tools effectively and safely"@en ;
  curric:slug "using-data-science-and-ai-tools-effectively-and-safely" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils will explore how data science and AI tools are having an
  impact on our daily lives. They will develop an understanding of how to use these tools
  effectively as well as an awareness of the issues relating to trust, bias and
  misinformation."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """AI, machine learning and data science are part of pupils’ daily lives
  through the apps, websites and tools they already use at home and in school. This unit helps
  them reflect on these experiences and understand how such technologies shape the world around
  them. Pupils learn to use these tools effectively while recognising potential risks,
  developing the judgment needed to become safe, discerning and responsible users of emerging
  digital systems.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3241-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3241-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3241-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3241-4 ;
  curric:id "3241"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.741005Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-artificial-intelligence ,
    oakcurric:thread-impact-of-technology .

oakcurric:unit-3230
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Programming: iteration"@en ;
  curric:slug "programming-iteration" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils discover how iteration is used to replicate parts of a
  program. They will analyse the difference between count and condition controlled iteration
  and how trace tables can be used to trace through loops. They will explore data validation
  techniques and robust program design."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Pupils continue to revisit core programming concepts to strengthen and
  deepen their understanding. This unit focuses on iteration, building on familiar ideas while
  introducing greater complexity in how loops are applied to solve problems. By refining their
  skills in structuring and controlling the flow of programs, pupils create code that is more
  efficient to code and more adaptable. This progression prepares them to tackle more
  sophisticated, real-world programming tasks with confidence and independence.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3230-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3230-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3230-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3230-4 ;
  curric:id "3230"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.893359Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-programming ,
    oakcurric:thread-algorithms-and-data-structures ,
    oakcurric:thread-impact-of-technology .

oakcurric:unit-3226
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Programming: sequence"@en ;
  curric:slug "programming-sequence" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will discover computers process instructions. They will
  recognise the function and tools IDEs provide for developing code and start to develop
  Python programa which follow a sequence. Pupils will create programs which deal with input
  and output and make variables to store values."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As pupils begin their GCSE Computer Science course, it is vital they
  secure a strong understanding of the fundamental principles of programming. A clear grasp of
  how programs are structured and how data is managed equips pupils to tackle the increasingly
  complex challenges they will face. The unit concludes with a practical project, giving pupils
  the opportunity to bring these concepts together in a purposeful way which is an essential
  foundation for success in GCSE Computer Science and beyond.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3226-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3226-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3226-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3226-4 ;
  curric:id "3226"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:24.896310Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-algorithms-and-data-structures ,
    oakcurric:thread-programming .

oakcurric:unit-3243
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Programming: dictionaries and data files"@en ;
  curric:slug "programming-dictionaries-and-data-files" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces pupils to the new data structures of records and
  dictionaries. They will develop a Caesar cipher encryption program using a dictionary as a
  cipher wheel. Pupils will explore how data can be read from and written to files and how
  this data can be used within a program."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As pupils enter the final stage of their GCSE programming journey, they
  are ready to manage data in more sophisticated and structured ways. This unit introduces new
  methods for storing and accessing information, encouraging pupils to think critically about
  how data is organised and used. Through applying structured approaches to records, lists and
  dictionaries, they strengthen their problem-solving and analytical thinking. Reflecting on
  how data is stored and retrieved helps pupils consider the growing role of data in modern
  computing and the responsibility of those who create and manage it.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3243-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3243-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3243-3 ;
  curric:id "3243"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.038565Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-programming ,
    oakcurric:thread-algorithms-and-data-structures .

oakcurric:unit-3228
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Programming: selection"@en ;
  curric:slug "programming-selection" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will explore the benefits of good programing practices and why
  subroutines are used in programs. They will create conditions in programs which use
  arithmetic, relational and logical expressions. They will develop their understanding of
  selection and explore nested selection."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Having already strengthened their understanding of sequences, pupils are
  now ready to explore how programs make decisions. Selection is introduced at this stage to
  help pupils move beyond linear code and begin writing programs that can adapt to different
  situations. Understanding how conditions control program flow and how logical expressions are
  evaluated develops their problem-solving and computational thinking. This ensures pupils can
  design more purposeful and responsive programs, laying the groundwork for tackling
  increasingly complex challenges in computer science.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3228-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3228-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3228-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3228-4 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3228-5 ;
  curric:id "3228"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.044280Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-programming ,
    oakcurric:thread-algorithms-and-data-structures .

oakcurric:unit-3240
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "IT and the world of work"@en ;
  curric:slug "it-and-the-world-of-work" ;
  rdfs:comment """Pupils must be able to identify how the modern structure of the workplace will
  impact their future lives. This unit will facilitate a deeper comprehension of the methods
  employed by organisations and the impact the use of IT in the working environment has on
  all stakeholders."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As pupils prepare for life beyond school, they build on experiences of
  technology gained at home and in school to understand how IT shapes the modern workplace.
  This unit explores how digital tools support collaboration, remote work, and communication,
  and how these changes affect both organisations and employees. Pupils also consider issues of
  accessibility and inclusivity, helping them recognise the skills and awareness needed to
  thrive in a digital world of work.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3240-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3240-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3240-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3240-4 ;
  curric:id "3240"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.138987Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-design-and-development ,
    oakcurric:thread-effective-use-of-tools .

oakcurric:unit-3249
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "HTML programming project"@en ;
  curric:slug "html-programming-project" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will explore how websites are displayed within a browser using
  HTML and CSS. They will examine how websites are requested and delivered to our computer
  via the internet and the WWW. They will create the structure of a website using HTML and
  change the styling using CSS."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit progresses pupils understanding of how the internet works
  through the context of programming. Pupils will gain an understanding of how websites are
  displayed within a browser using HTML and CSS, progressing on to using JavaScript to make
  these pages interactive. This unit is a culmination of pupils journey in learning programming
  by guiding them through a project that allows them to develop designing, writing, testing and
  refinement skills when developing a high-level text-based program.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3249-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3249-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3249-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3249-4 ;
  curric:id "3249"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.162539Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-programming ,
    oakcurric:thread-design-and-development .

oakcurric:unit-3234
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Programming: strings and lists"@en ;
  curric:slug "programming-strings-and-lists" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces pupils to string-handling techniques, they will explore how a
  string can be iterated over using a loop and sliced to create substrings. Pupils will be
  introduced to arrays and lists and explore the differences between the two. They will
  manipulate with a variety of list methods."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As pupils become more confident programmers, they are ready to extend
  their understanding of how data can be organised and manipulated within programs. This unit
  builds on earlier work with text and data structures, introducing more sophisticated ways to
  store, access, and modify information. Understanding how to handle strings and lists enables
  pupils to create programs that are more efficient and adaptable. Developing these skills now
  strengthens their logical thinking and prepares them to design solutions that manage and
  process larger sets of data effectively.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3234-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3234-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3234-3 ;
  curric:id "3234"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.223034Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-programming ,
    oakcurric:thread-algorithms-and-data-structures .

oakcurric:unit-3253
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Spreadsheets"@en ;
  curric:slug "spreadsheets" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will explore how to use spreadsheets to store and manipulate
  data. They will use common functions and extract data to create visual representations
  using charts. Pupils will use spreadsheets to track and calculate income, make
  predictions, and answer “what if…?” questions."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Spreadsheets are a versatile tool used in a range of different contexts.
  As pupils reach the end of year 11 they will increasingly find more opportunities to use them
  in more complex ways. This unit will extend the basics of spreadsheets covered in previous
  units and provide pupils with the knowledge to build spreadsheets that will be robust and
  present data effectively. The culmination of the unit provides an opportunity for pupils to
  apply this understanding to a genuine scenario they may face when they leave school.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3253-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3253-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3253-3 ;
  curric:id "3253"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.335431Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-data-and-information ,
    oakcurric:thread-effective-use-of-tools .

oakcurric:unit-3231
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Boolean logic"@en ;
  curric:slug "boolean-logic" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will discover that Boolean logic is a way of describing
  circuits inside a computer. They will recognise logic gates as the building blocks of
  processors. They will be able to construct logic diagrams, truth tables and simplify
  Boolean expressions."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Having already encountered logic gates when studying computer systems,
  pupils are now ready to deepen their understanding of how Boolean logic underpins the
  operation of modern processors. This unit helps them see how simple logical operations can be
  combined to solve problems, linking abstract logic to practical computing. Learning Boolean
  logic develops pupils’ ability to think critically, structure arguments, and apply systematic
  reasoning, which is valuable in everyday decision-making.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3231-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3231-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3231-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3231-4 ;
  curric:id "3231"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.352686Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-algorithms-and-data-structures .

oakcurric:unit-3232
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Programming: subroutines"@en ;
  curric:slug "programming-subroutines" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will be introduced to structured programming. They will
  explore the differences between functions and procedures and use functions to return
  values in programs. They will be introduced to the concept of scope and how parameters can
  be used to reduce the need for global variables."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """Having already developed confidence with sequences, selection and
  iteration, pupils are now ready to structure their programs more effectively. This unit
  introduces subroutines, showing how breaking problems into smaller, reusable parts. Pupils
  build on their earlier use of built-in functions by learning to write their own, helping them
  appreciate the importance of decomposition in programming. Crucially, this way of thinking by
  dividing complex challenges into manageable steps and is a valuable skill beyond computer
  science, supporting problem-solving across subjects and in everyday life.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3232-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3232-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3232-3 ;
  curric:id "3232"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.440198Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-programming ,
    oakcurric:thread-algorithms-and-data-structures .

oakcurric:unit-3245
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Python programming project"@en ;
  curric:slug "python-programming-project" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will have the opportunity to apply the skills and knowledge
  they have developed in previous programming units by approaching a practical project. They
  will apply software design, product design and testing principles to take their project
  from initial design to working prototype."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit brings together all of the programming concepts and techniques
  that pupils have developed throughout KS4. They will develop their project management skills
  to approach a practical programming project. They will learn software design principles as
  well as how to document development and testing throughout a programming project.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3245-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3245-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3245-3 ;
  curric:id "3245"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.497213Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-programming .

oakcurric:unit-3247
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Databases and SQL"@en ;
  curric:slug "databases-and-sql" ;
  rdfs:comment """This unit introduces pupils to databases and SQL, they will explore the key terms
  used in a database and why relational databases are used to eliminate the redundancy that
  can occur in a flat file database. They will explore SQL commands to retrieve, update, and
  delete data in a relational database."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit introduces pupils to the world of databases and SQL. Pupils will
  have worked with datasets in KS3 but will not have experienced data management systems.
  Pupils will explore the key terms used in a database and learn why relational databases are
  used to eliminate the redundancy and inconsistencies that can occur in a flat file database.
  Pupils will explore increasingly challenging SQL commands where they retrieve, update, and
  delete data in a relational database. To conclude the unit pupils will investigate the legal,
  ethical and environmental impacts of data and data systems.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3247-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3247-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3247-3 ;
  curric:id "3247"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.546457Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-impact-of-technology ,
    oakcurric:thread-data-and-information .

oakcurric:unit-3239
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Online safety"@en ;
  curric:slug "online-safety" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit, pupils will evaluate the online world and their own internet
  activity for safety concerns in order to equip themselves with tools for protecting their
  online identities. They key takeaway of this unit is a repository of practical,
  risk-reducing steps that pupils can implement online."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As most pupils already have an online presence and experience of digital
  spaces, this unit encourages them to think more critically about their own behaviour and the
  actions of others online. It challenges pupils to engage with important debates, such as the
  balance between personal privacy and the powers of organisations or governments. By
  developing their own ideas and opinions, pupils grow into thoughtful and responsible digital
  citizens, able to navigate the online world with confidence and an understanding of their
  rights and responsibilities.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3239-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3239-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3239-3 ;
  curric:id "3239"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.601864Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-impact-of-technology ,
    oakcurric:thread-safety-and-security .

oakcurric:unit-3254
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Using IT in project management"@en ;
  curric:slug "using-it-in-project-management" ;
  rdfs:comment """Project management has numerous transferable skills for pupils, from simple time
  management to structured project management techniques. In this unit pupils will have the
  opportunity to develop invaluable skills in using common software tools and systems used
  for project management."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit draws together knowledge from a range of previous units
  throughout the whole curriculum and develops and understanding of how technology can be used
  to better organise and plan work. Using common office software, pupils leaving year 11 will
  appreciate how they can apply what they have learnt to real-life situations.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3254-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3254-2 ;
  curric:id "3254"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.603991Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-data-and-information ,
    oakcurric:thread-effective-use-of-tools .

oakcurric:unit-3229
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Computer Systems"@en ;
  curric:slug "computer-systems" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will discover the difference between general purpose and
  embedded systems. They will examine computer architecture and the components that make up
  a processor. Pupils will recognise the need for storage and be able to select a suitable
  storage device for a given purpose."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """As pupils progress through the GCSE, it is important they understand what
  happens inside the computer systems they rely on every day. This unit gives them the
  knowledge to see beyond the screen, showing how simple logical operations form the foundation
  of all computing processes. By understanding how data is stored and managed, pupils can make
  informed decisions about storage solutions and appreciate the trade-offs between different
  technologies. Exploring the environmental impact of computing encourages pupils to think
  critically about how digital systems affect the world.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3229-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3229-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3229-3 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3229-4 ;
  curric:id "3229"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:25.932712Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-computing-systems .

oakcurric:unit-3251
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Digital media"@en ;
  curric:slug "digital-media" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will develop pre-production skills used in digital media. They
  will learn the importance of understanding client requirements, planning, developing
  timeframes and the steps involved in these processes. They will be exposed to a variety of
  software tools and learn how to use them."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """This unit develops pupils' understanding of pre-production skills used in
  digital media industries. They will learn the importance of understanding the client's
  requirements, planning, developing timeframes and deadlines, and the techniques involved in
  these processes. They will then learn a number of the different software tools to fulfil
  basic client briefs. Pupils will apply this knowledge and develop their own digital media
  creation from a set of provided briefs. They will then assess each other's projects in terms
  of their effectiveness at meeting the aims of the brief.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3251-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3251-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3251-3 ;
  curric:id "3251"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.105326Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-creating-media ,
    oakcurric:thread-design-and-development .

oakcurric:unit-3227
  a curric:Unit ;
  rdfs:label "Algorithms"@en ;
  curric:slug "algorithms" ;
  rdfs:comment """In this unit pupils will discover the computational thinking techniques;
  decomposition, abstraction and algorithmic thinking. They will reflect on differences
  between algorithms and computer programs and explore how algorithms can be represented.
  Pupils will explore the impact of algorithmic bias."""@en ;
  curric:whyThisWhyNow """In this unit pupils develop the problem-solving and logical thinking
  skills that underpin success in computer science. Understanding algorithms helps them break
  down complex problems into manageable steps. By learning to represent algorithms through
  flowcharts, pseudocode and code, pupils gain the tools to think systematically and express
  solutions clearly. This deepens their understanding of how computers process instructions
  while also strengthening their reasoning and decision-making skills across subjects and
  everyday life.""" ;
  curric:hasPriorKnowledgeRequirement
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3227-1 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3227-2 ,
    oakcurric:priorknowledge-3227-3 ;
  curric:id "3227"^^xsd:positiveInteger;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:29:26.858694Z"^^xsd:dateTime ;
  curric:isUnitOf
    natcurric:scheme-computing-key-stage-4 ;
  curric:includesThread
    oakcurric:thread-programming ,
    oakcurric:thread-algorithms-and-data-structures ,
    oakcurric:thread-impact-of-technology .

